#rerun model with other distances
set.seed(120)
#kmeans clustering, using manhattan distance
k4 = kcca(university1, k=4, kccaFamily("kmedians"))
#Apply the predict() function
clusters_index <- predict(k4)
dist(k4@centers)
##          1        2        3
## 2 3.342420                  
## 3 4.463606 5.763296         
## 4 2.442504 5.639068 4.203004
image(k4)
points(university1, col=clusters_index, pch=19, cex=0.3)

#using elbow chart to determine k
set.seed(100)
# Scaling the data frame (z-score) 
fviz_nbclust(university1, kmeans, method = "wss")

fviz_nbclust(university1, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

#Create the cluster index for 3 clusters
set.seed(100)
k3_median = kcca(university1, k=3, kccaFamily("kmedians"))
clusters_index_3 <- predict(k3_median)
#Merging the clusters to the original data frame
university_analysis<-na.omit(universities)
set.seed(100)
clusters <- data.frame(clusters_index_3)
University_Analysis<- cbind(university_analysis, clusters)
#Cluster summary statistics analysis
Cluster_Statistics <- University_Analysis %>%group_by( clusters_index_3 ) %>%
summarise( Acceptance_rate = sum(X..appl..accepted)/ sum(X..appli..rec.d), Avg_out_state_tuition=mean(out.of.state.tuition), Avg_int_state_tuition=mean(in.state.tuition), Avg_room_cost=mean(room), Avg_board_cost=mean(board),fac.w.PHD=mean(X..fac..w.PHD), stud_fac_ratio=mean(stud..fac..ratio), Grad_rate=mean(Graduation.rate))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
Cluster_Statistics

# it can be infered that schools in cluster2 are Ivy league schools; schools in cluster3 are mid range schools/private schools; while schools in cluster 1 are public schools.
#schools in cluster2 have lowest acceptance rate, highest tuition; same tuition for in-state and out of state; highest room and board rates, highest faculty with PHD; lowest Student:faulty ratio; highest Graduation rates; these are features  
# schools in cluster 3 are at midpoint for acceptance rate,tuition,stu:faculty ratio, graduation rate and are 93% private schools
# schools in cluster 1 are 94% public schools and have the lowest numbers for most of the variables
# using the categorical measurements (State and Private/Public) to characterize the different clusters. Is there any relationship between the clusters and the categorical information?

Private_Public <- University_Analysis %>%group_by( clusters_index_3 ) %>%
summarise( Acceptance_rate = sum(X..appl..accepted)/ sum(X..appli..rec.d), Avg_out_state_tuition=mean(out.of.state.tuition), Avg_int_state_tuition=mean(in.state.tuition), Avg_room_cost=mean(room), Avg_board_cost=mean(board),fac.w.PHD=mean(X..fac..w.PHD), stud_fac_ratio=mean(stud..fac..ratio), Grad_rate=mean(Graduation.rate), priv_count = sum(Public..1...Private..2. == 2), pub_count = sum(Public..1...Private..2. == 1))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

#Cluster 1 which has the lowest  tuition,room and board cost, graduation rate and has the highest student:faculty ratio is 94% public schools.

#What other external information can explain the contents of some or all of these clusters?
# it is common knowledge that private schools are more expensive than public schools, have higher graduation rates and  have lower student:faculty ratio
#Consider Tufts University, which is missing some information. Compute the Euclidean distance of this record from each of the clusters that you found above (using only the measurements that you have). Which cluster is it closest to? 
k3 <- kmeans(university1, centers = 3, nstart = 25)
#f. Isolating the data to Tufts University cluster 2 had the lowest distance
Tufts <- filter(universities, College.Name == "Tufts University")
Tufts <- predict(norm.values, Tufts)

#Euclidean Distance for Each Cluster 
dist(rbind(Tufts, k3$centers[1,]))

#Impute NAs with average from cluster 2
cluster_2 <- filter(University_Analysis, clusters_index_3 == 2)
names(Tufts)[sapply(Tufts, anyNA)]

Tufts[, c(10)] <- avg_cluster_2
